				<section class="elementor-element elementor-element-52b0090 elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default elementor-section elementor-top-section" data-id="52b0090" data-element_type="section">
						<div class="elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default">
				<div class="elementor-row">
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-4fe3273 elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column" data-id="4fe3273" data-element_type="column">
			<div class="elementor-column-wrap  elementor-element-populated">
					<div class="elementor-widget-wrap">
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-980cb6c elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="980cb6c" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix"><p>Today we are finally going over a project of mine. My in development music player &#8220;Magic MusicPlayer&#8221;. I’ll start with a short introduction of what it is and what I want to achieve with it. Then I jump right into the development. What works? What is planned? Where can you download it? In the end I’ll talk a bit about why I chose Java and JavaFX, as well as some problems with this decision.</p><p>If you do not want to read the website, but rather a nicely formatted pdf, or have to go offline in a bit, you can download one <span style="color: ##bff2ff;"><a style="color: ##bff2ff;" href="https://lucahohmann.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Blog_Post___Proframming__01.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="color: #00ccff;">here</span></a></span></p></div>
				</div>
